The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, June 5: The department of telecom will consult the finance ministry on issues related with spectrum charge, including the crucial entry fee for 3G spectrum. The DoT seeks to settle the contentious matters within a month. There is an internal deadline of 4-6 weeks to settle these. All finance related issues, including the Trai?s proposal to reduce the spectrum annual fee from 2-6 per cent to 4 per cent, would be taken up with the finance ministry.

 New Delhi, June 5: The Union power ministry would soon approach the cabinet with a proposal to allow projects below Rs 1,500 crore for automatic approval. Under the plan, an empowered committee would be set up headed by the power secretary, which would scrutinise projects with a cap of Rs 1,500 crore. The final approval would be given by the power minister.

 Calcutta, June 5: ONGC wants oil refining companies to pay the price of imported crude while buying from it. CMD Subir Raha said the difference between what ONGC gets and the landed cost is to the tune of $2.5 per barrel for the same quality of crude.

 New Delhi, June 5: Robust earnings and higher tax payment by India Inc pushed up the Centre?s gross tax collection by 20 per cent to Rs 3,04,980 crore in 2004-05. The government mopped up a whopping Rs 71,651 crore in March alone.

 New Delhi, June 5: Hero Honda today said it would invest up to Rs 600 crore over the next two years for new facilities. The company would set up a new plant and enter the scooter market by next year, managing director Pawan Kant Munjal said.




